Removing Stopwords¶

In [111]:
def remove_stopwords(text):
    words = text.split()
    filtered_words = [word for word in words if word.lower() not in set(stopwords.words('english'))]
    return ' '.join(filtered_words)

# Load the CSV file for the "Food Court" category
food_court_df = pd.read_csv('C:\\Users\\MOHAMMAD ANZIL\\Desktop\\New folder (14)\\Week3\\Week3-Team3-Novigo-\\Fodd-Week3\\Merged_category_dataset\\Restaurant_tweet.csv')

# Apply the remove_stopwords function to the "Tweet" column
food_court_df['Tweets'] = food_court_df['Tweet'].apply(remove_stopwords)

# Remove the "Tweet" column
food_court_df = food_court_df.drop(columns=['Tweet'])

# Overwrite the original CSV file with the cleaned data
food_court_df.to_csv('Food_Court_tweets.csv', index=False)

In [115]:
num_top_words = 10
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
topics=[]
In [116]:
# Extracting the topics from LDA model
for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(lda.components_):
    top_words_idx = topic.argsort()[:-num_top_words - 1:-1]
    top_words = [feature_names[i] for i in top_words_idx]
    topics.append(top_words)

for i, topic in enumerate(topics):
    print(f"Topic {i+1}: {',' .join(topic)}")

Wordcloud for Postive Tweets¶

In [118]:
from wordcloud import WordCloud

# WordCloud 
res = [' '.join(ele) for ele in topics]
text = ' '.join([word for word in res])
plt.figure(figsize=(20,15), facecolor='None')
wordcloud= WordCloud(max_words=500, width=1600, height=800).generate(text)
plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
plt.axis("off")
plt.title('Most frequent words in Positive Tweets (Restaurant)', fontsize=19)
plt.show()

Observation for Positive Tweets¶

1. High Praise for Food Quality:¶

  • Several positive tweets appreciate the restaurant's food quality, noting dishes like red sauce pasta or butter chicken as exceptional.¶

2. Ambiance and Experience:¶

  • Positive reviews often mention the ambiance, describing it as pleasant, well-thought, and offering a unique theme, as in the case of "Malgudi".¶

3. Service and Staff:¶

  • Many tweets commend the staff's helpfulness, courtesy, and professionalism, and they mention that the service is impressive.¶

4. Variety of Choices:¶

  • Customers often highlight the diverse menu options, with both continental and Indian dishes, as well as international cuisines..¶

Observation for Negative Tweets¶

1. Overpricing:¶

  • Negative tweets frequently complain about the high prices charged by the restaurants at the airport, indicating that the cost is unreasonable.¶

2. Lack Authenticity:¶

  • Some customers express dissatisfaction with the authenticity of regional or local dishes, implying that the taste does not match traditional standards.¶

3. Service Issues:¶

  • Service issues, such as delays in getting orders or rude behavior from restaurant staff.¶

4. Quality Discrepancies:¶

  • Customers may complain about quality discrepancies between what they expected and what they received, for instance, overcooked or tasteless food.¶
